If itâ€™s already a Git repo (has a .git folder), Git will be automatically enabled in VS Code.

ğŸ§± Step 4: Initialize Git (if not already a repo)

If the folder is not yet a Git repository:

Open the Source Control panel (sidebar icon or Ctrl + Shift + G)

Click "Initialize Repository"

Or run:

git init


Now VS Code will show Git options in the Source Control panel.

ğŸ” Step 5: Use Git Inside VS Code

You can now:

Task	How to do it
Stage changes	Click the + icon next to files
Commit changes	Type a message and click the âœ“ icon
Push/pull	Use bottom bar buttons or right-click in Source Control
View branches	Click the branch name in bottom left
Switch branches	Use the same branch menu or Command Palette (Ctrl+Shift+P)
Merge / Rebase	Use terminal or Command Palette
ğŸŒ Step 6: Connect to GitHub (Optional but Useful)
ğŸ“Œ Clone a GitHub Repo

